{
    "esm": "0.4.0",
    "metadata": {
        "name": "HeavisideBoundaryCondition",
        "description": "Smoothed Heaviside surface boundary condition for coupling surface and subsurface water flow, from Wang et al. (2020) (Advances in Water Resources 137, 103499), Eqs. 3 and 5. The component switches a single surface node continuously between a ponded (saturated) boundary and an unsaturated boundary as the pressure head h crosses zero, replacing a hard step with the smooth approximations eta_omega(h) = (1/pi)*atan(h/omega) + 1/2 (smoothed Heaviside, Eq. 5a) and delta_omega(h) = (1/pi)*omega/(omega^2 + h^2) (smoothed Dirac delta, Eq. 5b; delta_omega = d eta_omega/dh). The head obeys the boundary condition d/dt[eta_omega(h)*h] = P - I_infil (Eq. 3), stated as the explicit ODE D(h) = (P - I_infil)/(delta_omega*h + eta_omega). h is the single integrated state; eta_omega and delta_omega are algebraic (observed). Migrated from EnvironmentalTransport.jl@a48559c4 src/surface_runoff.jl:232 (`HeavisideBoundaryCondition` @component). Because the head equation conserves eta_omega(h)*h - (P - I_infil)*t, every ODE-integration test below is checked against the exact conservation law, not merely against a prior solver run.",
        "tags": [
            "environmental-transport",
            "surface-runoff",
            "boundary-condition",
            "smoothed-heaviside",
            "saint-venant",
            "wang-2020"
        ],
        "created": "2026-05-17T00:00:00Z",
        "authors": [
            "EnvironmentalTransport.jl contributors",
            "EarthSciModels migration (esm-5prg)"
        ],
        "references": [
            {
                "citation": "Wang, Z., Timlin, D., Kouznetsov, M., Fleisher, D., Li, S., Tully, K., & Reddy, V. (2020). Coupled model of surface runoff and surface-subsurface water movement. Advances in Water Resources, 137, 103499. Eqs. 3 and 5 -- the surface boundary condition d/dt[eta(h)*h] = P - I and the smoothed Heaviside / Dirac delta approximations eta_omega and delta_omega.",
                "doi": "10.1016/j.advwatres.2019.103499",
                "url": "https://doi.org/10.1016/j.advwatres.2019.103499"
            }
        ]
    },
    "models": {
        "HeavisideBoundaryCondition": {
            "reference": {
                "notes": "source_ref: EnvironmentalTransport.jl@a48559c4114eb9f06668ecf9f06235aad20f63f0:src/surface_runoff.jl:232 (`HeavisideBoundaryCondition` @component)\n\nUpstream `HeavisideBoundaryCondition` is an MTK `@component` building a raw `System(eqs, t)` from two `@constants` (one_over_pi = 1/pi, one_half = 0.5), three `@parameters` (omega, P, I_infil), three time-indexed `@variables` (h, eta_omega, delta_omega) and three equations. It implements the smoothed Heaviside surface boundary condition of Wang et al. (2020) -- the coupling device that lets a single surface node switch continuously between a ponded (saturated) boundary and an unsaturated boundary as the pressure head h crosses zero, without a hard `ifelse` branch.\n\nPhysics. Eq. 5a defines the smoothed Heaviside step eta_omega = (1/pi)*atan(h/omega) + 1/2, and Eq. 5b the smoothed Dirac delta delta_omega = (1/pi)*omega/(omega^2 + h^2). These converge to the true unit step and Dirac delta as omega -> 0+, and delta_omega is exactly d(eta_omega)/dh. The surface boundary condition Eq. 3 is d/dt[eta_omega(h)*h] = P - I_infil; expanding the time derivative with the product rule, (eta_omega'(h)*h + eta_omega(h))*dh/dt = P - I_infil, and since eta_omega'(h) = delta_omega(h) the component states the head equation as the explicit ODE D(h) = (P - I_infil)/(delta_omega*h + eta_omega).\n\nVariable classification. h is the single genuine state -- the only variable with a D(.) derivative. eta_omega and delta_omega are algebraic functions of h (no derivative); the bead's `features` list is `variables, parameters, observed` and these two are the `observed` quantities. All three are encoded as `type: state` with a defining entry in the `equations` array (eta_omega and delta_omega via plain lhs = rhs algebraic equations, h via a D(.) equation). This preserves the upstream pre-`mtkcompile` structure exactly: the raw `System(eqs, t)` has three unknowns and three equations -- the invariant the upstream structural test 'HeavisideBoundaryCondition - Structural Verification' (test/surface_runoff_test.jl:223-240) asserts (`length(equations(hbc)) == 3`; h, eta_omega, delta_omega all in `unknowns`). The encoding matches the verified sibling migrations whose algebraically-defined outputs are likewise `type: state` + `equations` entries (species_lifetime.esm, oh_production.esm). When the ESS runner compiles the model it eliminates the two algebraic equations, leaving h as the sole integrated state and eta_omega/delta_omega as observed -- exactly the upstream 'HeavisideBoundaryCondition - Compilation' test (test/surface_runoff_test.jl:242-249), which asserts `length(unknowns(mtkcompile(hbc))) == 1`.\n\nConstants. one_over_pi (1/pi) and one_half (0.5) are upstream MTK `@constants`. They are encoded as `type: parameter` with fixed defaults -- the rig-wide treatment of MTK constants, matching the verified sibling photostationary.esm (its `one` constant). They are mathematical constants, not tunable inputs. one_over_pi's default is the Float64 nearest 1/pi; every inline-test expected value below is evaluated with that exact Float64, as the runner evaluates the AST. No variable name collides with the ESS validator's reserved physical-constant registry {R, k_B, N_A}, so no rename was needed.\n\nConserved quantity -- exact ODE reference values. The head equation is, by construction, D(h) = (P - I_infil)/(d/dh[eta_omega(h)*h]), so d/dt[eta_omega(h(t))*h(t)] = P - I_infil exactly. The quantity Phi(h) := eta_omega(h)*h therefore evolves linearly in time: Phi(h(t)) = Phi(h0) + (P - I_infil)*t. Phi is strictly increasing in h (Phi'(h) = delta_omega*h + eta_omega lies in (0, 1) for all real h), so h(t) is the unique root of Phi(h) = Phi(h0) + (P - I_infil)*t. Every ODE-integration test below pins h(t) (and the algebraic eta_omega, delta_omega evaluated at it) to that root, computed by Newton iteration on the closed-form Phi -- an analytic reference, not a value read back from a prior solver run. The inline tests therefore check the runner's time integration against the exact conservation law of the model.\n\nDefault scenario. The upstream `@variables`/`@parameters` carry no defaults except omega = 1.0e-4 m. The `.esm` defaults assemble one self-consistent canonical scenario from the upstream test values: h = 0.01 m (1 cm ponded), P = 2.0e-6 m/s (~7.2 mm/hr), I_infil = 1.0e-6 m/s (~3.6 mm/hr), omega = 1.0e-4 m -- the exact configuration of the upstream test 'Net positive flux increases head' (test/surface_runoff_test.jl:293-309). The net flux P - I_infil = 1.0e-6 m/s > 0, so the default scenario ponds: the head rises slowly from 1 cm.\n\nUpstream test reproduction. The Julia suite (test/surface_runoff_test.jl) has six `@testitem`s for this component; all are reproduced:\n- 'Structural Verification' and 'Compilation' -- reproduced structurally: the file declares three `equations` entries and three `state` variables, and the runner loads + compiles it (eliminating eta_omega/delta_omega to observed) before any assertion is checked.\n- 'Smoothed Heaviside properties' (eta_omega(0) = 0.5; eta_omega -> 1 for h >> omega; eta_omega -> 0 for h << -omega) -- reproduced and tightened from the upstream atol 1e-10 / 1e-3 by tests `heaviside_at_transition_zero_flux`, `heaviside_deep_ponding`, `heaviside_deep_unsaturated`, plus the exact intermediate point `heaviside_head_equals_smoothing_scale` (h = omega gives eta_omega = (1/pi)*atan(1) + 1/2 = 0.75).\n- 'Smoothed delta function' (delta_omega(0) = 1/(pi*omega); delta_omega << its peak far from h = 0) -- reproduced and tightened from the upstream rtol 1e-6 by `delta_peak_at_transition` and `delta_decay_far_field`.\n- 'Net positive flux increases head' (P > I_infil ponds the surface) -- reproduced quantitatively by `default_ponding_100s` and `net_precipitation_raises_head`, which pin the integrated head to the conserved-quantity root rather than only asserting h(end) > h(0).\n- 'Transition from unsaturated to saturated' (h starts negative, precipitation drives it positive) -- reproduced by `unsaturated_to_saturated_transition` (h: -0.05 m -> +0.10 m over 10000 s), which pins both the zero-crossing midpoint and the endpoint.\nThe remaining tests extend coverage: the zero-net-flux equilibrium (P = I_infil holds h, eta_omega, delta_omega exactly constant), net infiltration draining the head, and the algebraic vars sampled across the ponded, transition and unsaturated regimes.\n\nTolerance rationale. Model-level default rel = 1.0e-6. Assertions at t = 0 and on the zero-net-flux equilibrium tests are tightened to rel = 1.0e-9 (or abs = 1.0e-12 where the expected value is exactly 0): at t = 0 there is no integration drift, and when P = I_infil the head derivative is exactly 0.0 so h -- and the algebraic eta_omega, delta_omega -- stay pinned to their initial values. eta_omega/delta_omega evaluate atan and a rational expression, correctly-rounded to ~1 ULP, leaving ample headroom under rel = 1.0e-9. ODE-integration endpoints keep rel = 1.0e-6 (the analytic conserved-quantity root vs. the runner's adaptive Tsit5/Rosenbrock23 integration at reltol 1e-10); the stiff fast-transient test `unsaturated_to_saturated_transition` uses rel = 1.0e-5. No assertion expects a non-finite value -- delta_omega*h + eta_omega = Phi'(h) > 0 for all real h, so the head ODE never divides by zero.\n\nUnit balance (verified). h, omega in m; P, I_infil in m/s; eta_omega, one_over_pi, one_half dimensionless; delta_omega in m^-1.\n  eta_omega   `one_over_pi*atan(h/omega) + one_half`: atan of (m/m) is dimensionless, [1]*[1] + [1] = [1].\n  delta_omega `one_over_pi*omega/(omega^2 + h^2)`: [1]*[m]/([m^2]) = [m^-1].\n  D(h)        `(P - I_infil)/(delta_omega*h + eta_omega)`: [m/s]/([m^-1]*[m] + [1]) = [m/s]/[1] = [m/s] = d[h]/d[t]. SI throughout; no unit conversion at parse or runtime.\n\nProvenance. Structural scaffold (variables, the three-equation AST) generated by EarthSciSerialization.mtk2esm walking the actual MTK `System` built by `HeavisideBoundaryCondition()`; metadata, units, reference, tolerances, tests and examples hand-authored. The scaffolder emitted no unresolved schema-gap markers; the bead's `blocking_gap` field is `none`."
            },
            "tolerance": {
                "rel": 1e-06,
                "abs": 1e-12
            },
            "variables": {
                "h": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.01,
                    "description": "Soil water pressure head at the surface node [m] (Wang et al. 2020, Eq. 3). h is the single genuine time-dependent unknown of the component: the only variable carrying a D(.) derivative. Its sign is the ponding indicator -- h >= 0 is the ponded (saturated) state where surface water has accumulated, h < 0 is the unsaturated state where the surface can still accept infiltration. The smoothed Heaviside eta_omega(h) and Dirac delta_omega(h) below switch the surface boundary condition continuously across h = 0 instead of with a hard branch. The default 0.01 m (1 cm of ponded water) places the canonical scenario in the ponded regime, matching the upstream test 'Net positive flux increases head' (test/surface_runoff_test.jl:293-309)."
                },
                "η_ω": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "1",
                    "description": "Smoothed Heaviside step function eta_omega(h) [dimensionless] (Wang et al. 2020, Eq. 5a): eta_omega = (1/pi)*atan(h/omega) + 1/2. A continuous approximation to the unit step H(h) that converges to it as omega -> 0+. eta_omega(0) = 1/2 exactly; eta_omega -> 1 as h/omega -> +inf (fully ponded) and -> 0 as h/omega -> -inf (fully unsaturated). It is the fraction by which the surface behaves as a ponded (Dirichlet-head) boundary. eta_omega has no D(.) derivative -- it is an algebraic function of h, encoded as `type: state` with a defining entry in `equations` (see notes); the ESS runner eliminates it to an observed variable at compile time."
                },
                "δ_ω": {
                    "type": "state",
                    "units": "m^-1",
                    "description": "Smoothed Dirac delta function delta_omega(h) [m^-1] (Wang et al. 2020, Eq. 5b): delta_omega = (1/pi)*omega/(omega^2 + h^2). delta_omega is exactly the derivative of the smoothed Heaviside with respect to head, delta_omega = d(eta_omega)/dh -- a Lorentzian that converges to the Dirac delta as omega -> 0+. It peaks at h = 0 with delta_omega(0) = 1/(pi*omega) and decays as 1/h^2 far from the transition. Like eta_omega it is algebraic in h (no D(.) derivative), encoded as `type: state` with a defining `equations` entry and eliminated to observed at compile time."
                },
                "ω": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m",
                    "default": 0.0001,
                    "description": "Smoothing parameter for the Heaviside/Dirac approximation [m] (Wang et al. 2020, Eq. 5). omega sets the head scale over which the surface boundary condition switches between the ponded and unsaturated states: the transition width of eta_omega and the half-width of the delta_omega Lorentzian are both O(omega). Smaller omega -> sharper switch (eta_omega -> true step, delta_omega -> true Dirac delta); larger omega -> smoother but less accurate. The upstream default 1.0e-4 m (0.1 mm) is small relative to typical ponded depths so the approximation is tight while keeping the ODE non-stiff."
                },
                "P": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 2e-06,
                    "description": "Precipitation / irrigation flux density at the surface [m/s] (Wang et al. 2020, Eq. 3). An externally-supplied forcing -- the rate at which water arrives at the surface node. Encoded as `type: parameter` because the component has no governing equation for it. The default 2.0e-6 m/s (~7.2 mm/hr, a moderate rain rate) is the value used in the upstream test 'Net positive flux increases head' (test/surface_runoff_test.jl:302). The surface boundary condition is driven by the net flux P - I_infil; with the defaults P - I_infil = 1.0e-6 m/s > 0, so the head rises."
                },
                "I_infil": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "m/s",
                    "default": 1e-06,
                    "description": "Infiltration flux density at the surface [m/s] (Wang et al. 2020, Eq. 3). An externally-supplied sink -- the rate at which water leaves the surface node into the subsurface. Encoded as `type: parameter` for the same reason as P. The default 1.0e-6 m/s (~3.6 mm/hr) is the value used in the upstream test 'Net positive flux increases head' (test/surface_runoff_test.jl:302). Only the net flux P - I_infil enters the head equation: P > I_infil ponds the surface (dh/dt > 0), P < I_infil drains it (dh/dt < 0), and P = I_infil holds the head fixed (dh/dt = 0)."
                },
                "one_over_pi": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.3183098861837907,
                    "description": "The constant 1/pi [dimensionless]. Declared upstream as an MTK `@constants` entry (one_over_pi = 1.0/pi) so that Eqs. 5a and 5b read in their textbook form; encoded here as `type: parameter` with a fixed default, the rig-wide treatment of MTK constants (cf. the sibling photostationary.esm `one`). It is a mathematical constant, not a tunable input -- leave it at its default. The default is the Float64 nearest 1/pi."
                },
                "one_half": {
                    "type": "parameter",
                    "units": "1",
                    "default": 0.5,
                    "description": "The constant 1/2 [dimensionless]. Declared upstream as an MTK `@constants` entry (one_half = 0.5) -- the additive offset that centres the smoothed Heaviside eta_omega on 1/2 at h = 0. Encoded as `type: parameter` with a fixed default, as for one_over_pi; it is a mathematical constant, not a tunable input."
                }
            },
